      <p>The savings are real, but they come from lower operational costs, not lower effort or expertise. Every client receives the same analytical rigour, strategic depth, and reporting quality that London agencies charge a premium for. The difference is that a Leeds consultancy does not need to cover a £50,000 annual office lease in Farringdon.</p>

      <h2>Understanding SEO ROI</h2>

      <p>SEO is an investment, not an expense. Understanding typical return timelines helps set realistic expectations and evaluate whether the investment makes commercial sense for your business.</p>

      <h3>Month 1-3: Foundation Phase</h3>
      <p>The first three months focus on technical fixes, on-page optimisation, and local SEO setup. During this phase, you should see improvements in crawlability, indexation, and Google Business Profile visibility. Some quick wins produce ranking improvements within weeks, particularly for local and long-tail keywords.</p>

      <h3>Month 4-6: Growth Phase</h3>
      <p>Content and link building begin compounding. New pages start ranking for target keywords. Existing pages climb as technical improvements and internal linking take effect. Most businesses see measurable increases in organic traffic during this period, with some keywords reaching page one positions.</p>

      <h3>Month 7-12: Acceleration Phase</h3>
      <p>Sustained effort produces compound returns. Domain authority grows. Content assets mature and attract natural links. The gap between your site and competitors widens. For a typical Leeds business investing £1,000 per month, the target is for organic traffic to deliver leads or sales worth multiples of the SEO investment within 12 months.</p>

      <h3>Typical ROI Benchmarks</h3>
      <p>A Leeds solicitor paying £1,000 per month for SEO who acquires three new clients per month from organic search at an average case value of £2,000 generates £6,000 in monthly revenue from a £1,000 investment: a 6:1 return. An e-commerce brand generating an additional £5,000 in monthly sales from improved organic rankings against a £500 SEO spend achieves a 10:1 return. These are realistic benchmarks, not hypothetical maximums.</p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

